consent:
Research study: Understanding Gaming Experiences



Research team: This study is run by researchers at Queen Mary University of London, University of York, Australian Catholic University, and Imperial College London: 

- Nick Ballou (n.b.ballou@qmul.ac.uk)

- Dr Alena Denisova (alena.denisova@york.ac.uk)

- Prof Richard Ryan (Richard.Ryan@acu.edu.au)

- Prof Sebastian Deterding (s.deterding@imperial.ac.uk)

 

Queen Mary Ethics of Research Committee Reference: QMERC20.565.DSEECS22.117

___________________________________________________________



Thank you for considering taking part in this study. Please take a moment to read the following. The participant compensation in this study accounts for the time required to review this information, so no need to rush.

 

Participation in this study is entirely optional. If you choose not to take part, simply close this page and there will be with no disadvantages and you will hear no more about it.

 

Study aim: We want to develop a new questionnaire for measuring positive and negative video gaming experiences.

 

Who can participate: To participate, you need to:- have regularly played a video game recently

- be 18+ years old

- be proficient in English

 

What to expect: You will be asked to recall your recent experiences with a game, and then will rate a series of 50 statements on a scale from "strongly disagree" to "strongly agree" with reference to that game. 

 

In total, the study will take approximately 10 minutes.

 

Risks: Participating in this study is not expected to lead to any disadvantages, risks, or discomfort.

 

Confidentiality: We do not collect any personally identifying data. Your Prolific ID serves as a pseudonym that you can use to request access to your data. Prolific IDs will only be seen by the named researchers and not shared further.

 

How we will use your data: Your data will be used in research publications and/or conference presentations. Your data, which is non-identifying, will be stored indefinitely on the Open Science Framework, so that the data underlying the conclusions of any published work will remain available for inspection.

 

Legal basis: We will process your personal data for research purposes under Article 6 (1) (e) of the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR): Processing is necessary for the performance of a task carried out in the public interest.

 

Your rights to your data: Under the GDPR, you have a general right of access to your data, a right to rectification, erasure, restriction, objection or portability. You also have a right to withdrawal.

 

Withdrawal: You are free to withdraw within 1 month of data collection without any penalty or consequences. To do so, simply email the researcher with your Prolific ID. Your data will then be removed from the study. After 1 month, data will be anonymized and publicly shared, making withdrawal no longer be possible. 

 

Contact information: If you would like additional information about the study, or wish to remove your data after the study has ended, please contact the lead researcher Nick Ballou (n.b.ballou@qmul.ac.uk). If this is unsuccessful or not appropriate, please contact the Queen Mary Ethics of Research Committee: research-ethics@qmul.ac.uk.

recall-pos-text: Recently, while playing Gothic, I decided to try my hand at fighting one of the toughest opponents - the dragon. After many hours of gathering the best equipment and preparations, I finally came face to face with the beast. It was a truly epic battle in which I had to use all my skills and experience to survive. Fortunately, after much hardship and sacrifice, I managed to defeat the dragon. I was really happy with this success and felt like a real hero. I like this game because it has a great storyline, interesting characters and a world that you can explore and discover in any way you want. In addition, Gothic has a unique graphical style and music that perfectly sets the mood of the game world. One aspect that can be improved in Gothic is the artificial intelligence of the enemies. Sometimes they seem too easy to defeat or too predictable. Also, some missions are too difficult or unintuitive, which may discourage some players. However, despite these imperfections, I think Gothic is one of the best RPGs and I will always have a fondness for this title.

I have been trying to get a legendary (highest tier) accessory which is obtained by completing numerous achievements in specific maps in the game. Occasionally random events happen and organised group events also happen, such as raids or other guild events. 

What I enjoy most about the game is the "horizontal progression", which means that upon reaching the maximum level (80) of a character, this progress will not be diminished by future releases, rather new content simply adds on to your characters and what they can do, which is different to most MMOs where generally new content means older content is less or no longer relevant.

The game is of course by no means perfect, and a lot of the menus and navigation seems very dated compared to other games, and the lack of addons available mean you can see or analyze your performance a lot less compared to other games. This can definitely take some getting used to and is certainly frustrating at times
